(The present analysis examined whether sleep and targeted cueing jointly shape recall) Tj
0 -14 Td
(performance. Three conclusions follow directly from the data pattern. First, sleep was) Tj
0 -14 Td
(associated with robustly higher recall compared with wake, consistent with a large body of) Tj
0 -14 Td
(consolidation research. Second, cueing was associated with additional performance gains,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(consistent with the idea that reactivation can strengthen memory traces. Third, the interaction) Tj
0 -14 Td
(was statistically weak, indicating that cueing benefits were not uniquely restricted to sleep) Tj
0 -14 Td
(in this specific dataset.) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(From a theoretical standpoint, the significant sleep effect aligns with systems consolidation) Tj
0 -14 Td
(accounts in which offline neural dynamics facilitate transformation and stabilization of) Tj
0 -14 Td
(memory. The observed cueing effect also aligns with reactivation frameworks, suggesting that) Tj
0 -14 Td
(sensory prompts linked to prior learning can bias subsequent retrieval success. Importantly,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(the absence of a strong interaction does not invalidate sleep-specific mechanisms; instead, it) Tj
0 -14 Td
(narrows interpretation. One possibility is that cueing in both states provided some retrieval) Tj
0 -14 Td
(or rehearsal-related benefit, while sleep conferred an independent consolidation advantage.) Tj
0 -14 Td
(Another possibility is that the dataset aggregates over participant-level moderators \(e.g.,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(encoding strength, circadian phase, arousal\) that could obscure conditional effects.) Tj
0 -14 Td
() Tj
0 -14 Td
(The current findings are compatible with, but somewhat simpler than, results from high-control) Tj
0 -14 Td
(sleep-laboratory studies. Rasch et al. \(2007\) and related work emphasize that cue benefits can) Tj
0 -14 Td
(be strongest when cues are presented during specific sleep stages and under controlled sensory) Tj
0 -14 Td
(parameters. If the present protocol used broader or less stage-specific cueing windows,) Tj
0 -14 Td
(interaction attenuation would be expected. Similarly, reviews by Oudiette and Paller \(2013\)) Tj
0 -14 Td
(note that cue efficacy can depend on avoiding micro-arousals and matching cue intensity to) Tj
0 -14 Td
(perceptual thresholds. Without physiological recordings in the current dataset, such) Tj
0 -14 Td
(process-level distinctions cannot be tested.) Tj
